</div>

<h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">V Tile Strategy</h2>

<div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Dump V early:</span> V gets harder to play as the game progresses because vowels dry up. Play V within 1-2 turns — even a modest 6-8 point play beats getting stuck with it at endgame.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">VEX is your best friend:</span> At 13 points for just 3 letters, VEX is one of the highest point-per-tile words in the game (4.3 avg). Always check if X is available when you draw V.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
    <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Know your V-ending words:</span> Most English words don't end in V, but REV, DEV, GOV, LUV, and TAV are all valid. These are essential for parallel plays when V must go at the end of your word.</p>
  </div>
</div>

